Finding research participants for new products or technologies can be very difficult and even feel impossible. In this video, Helen breaks down some techniques researchers can use to better understand the product or tech they''re working on even if traditional methods of recruitment are out of reach.

[https://joinlearners.com/talk/how-to-break-the-barrier-of-finding-users-and-talking-to-them-in-early-stage-tech-startup-product](https://joinlearners.com/talk/how-to-break-the-barrier-of-finding-users-and-talking-to-them-in-early-stage-tech-startup-product)

 Key Takeaways

 Users of future and early stage products exist now, they''re just presently doing something else.

 In identifying users, there''s a lot of power in secondary research. How might we learn from similar or tangential spaces? What are the analogues?

 When talking to these users, stay away from the hypotheticals. Be grounded in the now. Identify the current tasks, tools or technology that they''re using in their current environment.

 User research in nascent spaces involves going out, observing and interviewing folks as they perform their typical tasks in their natural environment.', 'https://joinlearners.com/talk/how-to-break-the-barrier-of-finding-users-and-talking-to-them-in-early-stage-tech-startup-product', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE slug='random-collection-wip'), 'note', NULL, NULL, 'coda', 'published') ON CONFLICT(coda_row_id) DO UPDATE SET title=excluded.title, description=excluded.description, url=excluded.url, category_id=excluded.category_id, type=excluded.type, author=excluded.author, image_url=excluded.image_url, updated_at=current_timestamp;
The Kano Model measures factors across two measures:
The delight and disappointment levels of the customer
How successful the product is at meeting the product requirements (according to the customer)
Before you apply Kano Model Analysis, be sure to find out what your customers really value.

The Kano Analysis helps and prioritize which attributes of your product are most important to the customer. It is measured by the following:
Required (atari mae or “quality element”)
Desired (ichi gen teki or “one-dimensional quality element”)
Exciter/Delighter (mi ryoku teki or “attractive quality element”)
Neutral (mu kan shin or “indifferent quality element”)
